	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Changes I'd have made to LDoN</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><b>1.  More Variety, More Balance in mission selection.</b><br />
I'd have added some more incentive to do Assassinations and Rescues.  Zone Progression(can access better and more difficult bosses the more you kill), Rank Progression(Get higher standing for killing bigger bosses), Dropped Loot(obvious), or an alternate points system(dangerously complicated).  For rescues, it could be similar and you'd get status or plot advancement for rescuing certian individuals.<br />
<br />
Just how they divide incentives to do the different themes, I'd have used some incentive other than a tedius selection process to get people to take a variety of mission types.  I'd want people saying &quot;that was a fun assassinate, let's do a slaughter this time,&quot; not &quot;try for slaughter, but high collects are ok too if the RNG is being a bitch.&quot;<br />
<br />
I would make interesting bosses as well, with memorable names and abilities.  Perhaps even a dragon type encounter-- at the group(think East Wastes), not raid level.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>2.  No Collections</b> <br />
I'd have nixed collection missions entirely.  They're not different enough fundamentally from slaughters.  You can get lucky and finish early, or you can get unlucky and finish late.  At most, I'd have added them as an option to enhance a slaughter mission somehow.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>3.  Better mob variety</b>  <br />
I'd have made more actual variety between dungeons, in terms of mob hitpoints and abilities.  It's decent the way it is, but imo it could be better.  Make them more characteristic of each theme.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>4.  Scale variety</b>  <br />
I'd have also liked a chance for each dungeon to have a &quot;wide-open&quot; style dungeon.  Never one that is gauranteed, so that people wouldn't flock to one over the other, but I'd have liked more variety in scale.  That was one of the things I always liked about EQ was its attention to scale.  Some zones would be big and imposing (Kael, Bastion of Thunder, Temple of Veeshan) while others would be small or otherwise cramped (LGuk, PoTorment, Chardok, PoHate)  LDoN is mostly all the same scale.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>5.  Extra fun</b>  <br />
I'd have added optional mini-adventures or sub-adventures, similar to chests and traps, but I'd make them more combat-oriented.  For instance you could get loot or bonus points for completing a &quot;PoJ trial-like&quot; wave encounter in the middle of a normal mission.  This is more complicated than typical EQ-lite and might be dangerous for that reason(judging by the number of people who still can't figure out how LDoN points work, anyway).</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
		<!-- edit note -->
			<div class="smallfont">			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
