	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>I would have given the themes a bit more of a static feeling by making the layout linear. You couldn't jump into a collection in DGuk E, because you'd have to work your way there.<br />
<br />
To start, I'd have moved the Wayfarer camps inside the themes, instead of having them out in zones where they shouldn't be. The camps themeselves would be in a normal non-instanced zone, like an entry hall. They'd have guards posted by the zones that lead you to the instanced zones, to make it look like they're actually guarding them from nasty critters.<br />
<br />
Between each instanced zone (A-I or whatever), you'd have a small static buffer zone which is not instanced, and contains a group of Wayfarer Brotherhood, which would allow you to port back to the entry hall, the last buffer zone, or continue on another adventure through the next instanced zone.<br />
<br />
It'd look sorta like this:<br />
<br />
1. Deepest Guk Entry Hall<br />
2. Deepest Guk A<br />
3. Deepest Guk Buffer Zone 1<br />
4. Deepest Guk B<br />
5. Deepest Guk Buffer Zone 2<br />
6. Deepest Guk C<br />
7. Deepest Guk Buffer Zone 3<br />
and so on...<br />
<br />
As you progressed through the different zones (A-I or whatever) they'd get progressively harder, but the rewards would be greater. Winning in each type of adventure per zone would flag you to progress to the next buffer zone, and allow you to progress to the next zone in the series.<br />
<br />
You could, if you wanted, sit in Deepest Guk A and do the same kind of adventure over and over, but progressing through the dungeon would open up new areas of that theme that you couldn't see any other way, getting new types of loot, and new types of monsters, and so on.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
